<h1>To Major General Charles Lee</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Cambridge Jany 23. 1776</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>I received your favour of the 16 Instt &amp; am exceedingly sorry to hear,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0001" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> that Congress countermanded the embarkation of the two Regiments Intended agt the Tories on Long Island. they I doubt not had their reasons;<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0002" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> But to me It appears that the period is arrived, when nothing less than the most decisive &amp; vigorous measures should be pursuedOur Enemies from the other side of the Atlantic will be sufficiently numerous, It highly concerns [us]<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0003" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0003-ptr">3</a> to have as few Internal ones as possible.</p>
<p>As Congress seem to have altered their views in this Instance, &amp; the men which went with you from Connecticut; are upon a very different footing from what I expected,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0004" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0004-ptr">4</a> It will be right to give Congress the earliest notice of your proceeding &amp; to disband your Troops as soon as you think circumstances will admit of It.</p>
<p>In consequence of the melancholy reverse of our Affairs in Canada, an Application was made to me for Succour, &amp; happy should I have been, If the situation of this Army could have afforded It. All I could do, was to lay the matter before this &amp; the Governments of Connecticut &amp; New-Hampshire, &amp; urge the expediency &amp; necessity of their sending a Reinforcement of three Regiments there immediatelyMr Trumbull &amp; his Council of Safety had anticipated my request, the other two Colonies have adopted the measureThe three Regiments are now raising, &amp; I would willingly hope will arrive in time to reinstate matters in that Quarter &amp; give them a more agreable aspect than they now have.</p>
<p>I shall be much Obliged by your pressing Col. McDougal to forward the shells mentioned in his letter of the 2 Instt as they are much wanted, &amp; also to spare me some powder If he possibly can:<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0005" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0005-ptr">5</a> you know our stock of this necessary Article is small &amp; inconsiderable, &amp; you know too that we [have]<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0006" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0006-ptr">6</a> a demand for a further supply.</p>
<span class="pb center" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-03-02-pb-0171">[171]</span>
<p>The progress in raising recruits for the New Army being very slow, I have applied to this Colony, Connecticut &amp; New Hampshire for Ten Regiments of Militia to continue in service till the 1st of April next, which they have Granted me;<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0007" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0007-ptr">7</a> As soon as they come in, &amp; I can get provided with proper means, I am determined to Attempt something. of this I would have you take no notice.</p>
<p>Within a few days past Several persons have come out of Boston. they all agree that Genl Clinton has gone upon some expeditionsome say he has between 4 &amp; 500 menothers, part of Two RegimentsWhat his force consists of is not precisely known, but I am almost certain he is gone with some. His destination must be South of this, &amp; very probably for New York. I thought it necessary to give you this Information, that you may be on your guard &amp; prepared to receive him as well as you can.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0008" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0008-ptr">8</a></p>
<p>I shall be glad to hear from you frequently, &amp; to be Informed of any Occurrences you may think material. I am D. Sir with great regard &amp;c.</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">G. W.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0122-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Book Copy: letters copied into a bound letter-book ]">LB</abbr>, in Robert Hanson Harrisons writing, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>; 
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>Harrison inadvertently wrote have.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>For Congresss reasons, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0076&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-03-02-0076-fn-0001#GEWN-03-03-02-0076-fn-0001" class="document">Lee to GW, 16 Jan. 1776, n.1</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>This word is taken from the <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>GW expected the Connecticut men to serve as volunteers without pay and was surprised that they were allowed the same wages as the Continental troops (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0020" class="document">Lee to GW, 5 Jan.</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0033" class="document">GWs instructions to Lee, 8 Jan.</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0069" class="document">Jonathan Trumbull, Sr., to GW, 15 Jan.</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0274" class="document">GW to Joseph Reed, 26 Feb.9 Mar. 1776</a>).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0054" class="document">GW to Alexander McDougall, 13 Jan.</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0105" class="document">McDougall to GW, 20 Jan. 1776</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0006">6</a>

   <p>This word is taken from the <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0007-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0007">7</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0073" class="document">Council of War, 16</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0092" class="document">18 Jan. 1776</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0008-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0122-fn-0008">8</a>

   <p>Gen. Henry Clinton (17301795), who was second in command in America to Gen. William Howe, sailed from Boston on 20 Jan. in the frigate <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Mercury</span> to take command of an expeditionary force that was ordered to restore royal authority in the southern colonies. Clinton was accompanied from Boston by a store ship and two transports carrying two companies of light infantry and some highlanders. He was to rendezvous off Cape Fear, N.C., with the main part of his force, seven regiments of infantry that were sailing from Ireland. On his way to Cape Fear Clinton stopped at New York and Hampton Roads, Va., to consult with royal officials and gather intelligence. He arrived at New York on 4 Feb., at Hampton Roads on 17 Feb., and at Cape Fear on 12
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-03-02-pb-0172">[172]</span>
March. The transports from Ireland were delayed, however, and arrived at various times between 18 April and 31 May. On 28 June Clintons force made an unsuccessful attack on Charleston, and in August it joined Howes army at Staten Island for the New York campaign. Clinton served as British commander in chief in America from 1778 to 1782.</p>

</div>
